I went to Lighthouse for the first time a few weeks ago because I wanted to support black owned business. The atmosphere was awesome but my service was horrible. Firstly, my food took 20 minutes for a steak bowl. I get all the way home to see that I had no meat in my bowl. Horrible. I called the restaurant to let them know, but no one answered the phone. I called several times within 30 minutes. I chalked that up as a loss. Yesterday I had out of town guests that are vegetarian so I took them to Lighthouse because it's a close healthy option that serves vegan and veggie options. Why not give them a second chance? 🤷🏾‍♀️ This time I ordered a steak quesadilla. Can't possibly mess that up right?! Not only did my guest and I wait 20 minutes for our food but my quesadilla had absolutely no CHEESE OR MEAT! I kindly go up to explain that this happened to me last time and ask for them to make it again. The cook which was the standing manager was very rude and acted like I was a bother. I waited 30 minutes for another quesadilla. My guests were done eating. I went up to the counter to see what was the probl and they said that my food was coming up. I waited 5 more minutes. Asked for my money back but they had brought the food as soon as I was asking for my money. I asked if I could get the food since I was leaving and the "manager"said that they don't do that. I kindly took my money and left. Poor customer service. I will never go to this restaurant again!

A friend and I went today for lunch...My first time visiting! For starters, although we were the only ones in line, we had to wait awhile without any acknowledgement of staff before placing our order. Upon placing our order for the Mango Salmon bowl, we were told that the price is $12.99 and 55 cents extra for brown rice. However, the menu on the two overhead flat screens it is listed at $10.99 with your choice of rice or pasta. In addition, we were told that the new price is affixed to a small sign on the counter glass and the new price hasn’t been updated on the flat screens.  At this point we decided to have lunch somewhere else. First off, as a new restaurant that’s Black Owned, the customer service should’ve been considerably better instead of constantly addressing your cute little kid that’s behind the counter. Secondly, please update your menu prices on all publications instead of having your customers look at a small sign that has a line going through the old price and has the new price written with a Sharpie... Really!?!? Finally, why raise the price of the Mango Salmon by $2 and charge extra for rice? After all the salmon (wo mango) & rice is $10.99. I hear the food is tasty. However, I won’t be in a hurry to visit anytime soon...We’ve got to do better!

We were the only ones in line so we didn't wait long. I can see how if there was a long line or if they had a lot of call in orders, it could take a while for the food to come up. But it's really solid food for a good price - worth the wait. And the locally made cookies - Cookies with Curves - were amazing. I definitely recommend this place. Good non-meat options for folks. Let me just say there is a lot of good that litehouse does to feed those in need....and the owner I've met before seems to be a really a great guy! Unfortunately, the staff really needs a bit more customer service training. Today, I ran over to Litehouse Grill before they closed on A Friday night to get the mango grilled salmon bowl. Two orders to be exact. I also ordered a lemonade and 2 orders of sweet potato fries. (approximately $37.00). I get home and there is NO salmon in one of the orders. One order of fries is hot and the other is not. I noticed that as the person was putting together my food, she was half paying attention, and of course the customer service was mediocre (just as I remembered when they were on 53rd street). The rice in the bowls-- hard and cold. This is the second time I visited since they moved to 55th street. Then it all came back today, the reason I stopped going in the first place. The mistakes that have always been made with my food and the mediocre customer service. I've gone to other food establishments for years, and have gotten a wrong order far less than I have at Litehouse. I have eaten there so many times and have continued to support the business, but the staff just can't seem to get it right. I get it....this is just another review, and life goes on, and they will keep making money, but I keep trying and I keep getting disappointed. I supported because of the good they do for others. The food has always been great when they get it right! It's such a great place when the staff gets it right. Of course, they are closed now.....(oh and they never gave me a receipt, just assumed I didn't want it want it and immediately processed the next person's order....at that point couldn't go back to retrieve MY receipt). I even asked an employee about the dessert (vegan cheesecake) and she couldn't even tell me the flavors. She could have looked at it and just read the label. But, didn't even bother to do that. Dang, I could have eaten at so many other places in Hyde Park tonight. Disappointed again and out of $37. Welp, At least the lemonade was good. I believe in what they do so much to feed others that are less fortunate so much, that I would probably still be willing to go back, if my order was even just a little better tonight. After tonight I won't be back at all!! #DisappointedAgain

This place is pretty cool.  It's like a black- owned Chipotle. They have this social concept where you basically pay it forward when after you purchase your meal,  you can opt to purchase another for a person experiencing homelessness.  You just buy it and they stick the receipt up on the way by the register,  so when someone in need comes in,  they pick the ticket that sounds good to them, and they get that meal for free.  My only issue with the place is that ran out of like 3 of the signature menu items right as i got up to the counter. I had to go with me 2nd choice bc the first was no longer available.  The line stayed full,  tho,  so it's clearly a popular spot in Hyde Park (Chicago, IL).
